The COVID-19 Vocabulary (COVoc) is an ontology containing terms related to the research of the COVID-19 pandemic. This includes host organisms, pathogenicity, gene and gene products, barrier gestures, treatments and more.

definition.val: Any term from the COVOC vocabulary
A cell-based assay that uses B cells.
Any person meeting the laboratory criteria for COVID-19.
Any conformational change in a protein that causes a part of the protein to become inaccessible.
A sample of feces.

A strategy whereby viruses may evade neutralizing antibodies. Some viral glycoproteins are heavily glycosylated by N- and O- linked glycans,  creating a so called glycan shield, which may decrease antibody binding  affinity and  facilitate evasion of neutralizing antibodies.
The ability of a foreign substance, such as an antigen, to provoke an immune response in the body of a human or other animal.

A medical specialty that deals with critically ill patients who have, are at risk of, or are recovering from conditions that may be life-threatening. It includes providing life support, invasive monitoring techniques, resuscitation, and end-of-life care.

Used with bacteria, viruses, fungi, protozoa, and helminths for the obtaining of pure strains or for the demonstration of the presence of or identification of organisms by DNA analyses, immunologic, or other methods, including culture techniques. It is used also with biological substances and chemicals for the isolation and purification of the constituents.

Analysis of microbial and host genetic material (DNA or RNA) in small-quantity samples from patients. It allows for identification and genomic characterization of bacteria, fungi, parasites, and viruses without the need for a priori knowledge of a specific pathogen directly from clinical specimens.
An assay based on binding to the major histocompatibility complex.
A sample taken from the nasopharyngeal tract.
A sample taken from the oropharyngeal tract.
A testing method that is significantly faster than others, e.g. 16s antibiograms vs. culture-based antibiograms.
A cell-based assay that uses T cells.
A T cell epitope is presented on the surface of an antigen-presenting cell, where it is bound to MHC molecules.
A widely used analytical technique in molecular biology and immunogenetics to detect specific proteins in a sample of tissue homogenate or extract.
Any person meeting the clinical criteria for COVID-19.
Any person meeting the clinical criteria for COVID-19 with an epidemiological link, or any person meeting the diagnostic criteria for COVID-19.
